00:21:12,880 --> 00:21:22,720
Product teams have a hierarchy of needs and we like to sort of point at the failures to meet

268
00:21:22,720 --> 00:21:32,400
elements of that hierarchy higher up the triangle and sort of impugn the failure of that organization for not as an example measuring adoption metrics very

269
00:21:32,400 --> 00:21:40,240
carefully and not closely tracking those metrics as a means by which to drive execution.

270
00:21:40,240 --> 00:21:46,960
When I jumped in, I was like, man, you know, we need to establish some some basic standards for test coverage.

271
00:21:46,960 --> 00:21:55,200
We need to establish some basic standards for how we do what I call a factory inspection on a product once it's ready to roll off the assembly line.

272
00:21:55,200 --> 00:21:58,240
Do we have a checklist for what we call product quality?

273
00:21:58,240 --> 00:22:00,400
And what does product quality mean?

274
00:22:00,400 --> 00:22:01,840
Those basic things weren't there.

275
00:22:01,840 --> 00:22:08,240
And so, the idea that we should be spending time measuring adoption metrics is absolute insanity.

276
00:22:08,240 --> 00:22:11,200
you're skipping a lot of steps between here and there.

277
00:22:11,200 --> 00:22:19,600
And so we have made great strides and I think it's translating to product quality improvements for our customers.

278
00:22:19,600 --> 00:22:26,720
But I feel as I said a little dumb for the way I was thinking about it before I jumped into the deep end.

279
00:22:26,720 --> 00:22:33,600
There is just no excuse as an executive for sitting outside of the mess and thinking you know the answers.

280
00:22:33,600 --> 00:22:36,480
It's a it's a cardinal sin as an executive to do that.

281
00:22:36,480 --> 00:22:37,760
you need to go and see.

282
00:22:37,760 --> 00:22:39,039
You need to be in the boiler room.

283
00:22:39,039 --> 00:22:44,880
You need to study the system bottom up and um and develop hypotheses for how to amend the system.

284
00:22:44,880 --> 00:22:46,320
And that's what I've been doing.

285
00:22:46,320 --> 00:22:51,600
I love hearing this because so many people have teams that are not functioning incredibly well.

286
00:22:51,600 --> 00:22:56,799
And hearing from someone that is not a longtime product person come in and try to fix these problems,

287
00:22:56,799 --> 00:22:59,840
I think is really useful and interesting for people to hear.

288
00:22:59,840 --> 00:23:02,000
to to dig into this a little bit more.

289
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:13,039
Um was the big lesson and kind of uh eye-opening moment that there's a lot of kind of foundational work that needs to happen to achieve this outcome that you're trying to achieve which is measure uh engagement and adoption.

290
00:23:13,039 --> 00:23:15,760
Well, is it like tracking and metrics and data science?

291
00:23:15,760 --> 00:23:17,840
Is that kind of the in the lesson there?

292
00:23:17,840 --> 00:23:28,640
The lesson is that everything must be done in its time and order and you can move really really quickly.

293
00:23:28,640 --> 00:23:37,200
Uh you can you can there's no sort of excuse not to move with urgency on all of these things,

294
00:23:37,200 --> 00:23:39,280
but you got to do them in order.

295
00:23:39,280 --> 00:23:43,120
And you have to you have to lead bottom up.

296
00:23:43,120 --> 00:23:48,080
Like you got to lead from the specific circumstances you observe.

297
00:23:48,080 --> 00:23:57,039
And I think for me, one of the best things that's happened over the last 11 months is that I've gained

298
00:23:57,039 --> 00:24:06,799
a greater trust in my own instincts that that the that the sort of patterns I've matched across other functions do indeed

299
00:24:06,799 --> 00:24:09,440
apply in product.

300
00:24:09,440 --> 00:24:17,279
But I have both the advantage and disadvantage of not having led a product function before and therefore must think about every problem from first principles.

301
00:24:17,279 --> 00:24:18,000
I have no choice.

302
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:19,760
I can read [ __ ] on the internet.

303
00:24:19,760 --> 00:24:29,600
I can like listen to clear thinkers on topics and import their ideas, but I'm very reluctant to import an idea without breaking it down into its constituent parts and figuring out how it applies at Rippling.

304
00:24:29,600 --> 00:24:37,360
And so I don't actually give a [ __ ] about adoption metrics uh as a matter of principle.

305
00:24:37,360 --> 00:24:43,360
I care about adoption metrics when I care about adoption metrics.

306
00:24:43,360 --> 00:24:47,039
Like I realize that that's a tautological statement, but it's like I'll get there.

307
00:24:47,039 --> 00:24:49,840
And so in certain parts of our product, I really do care about adoption metrics.

308
00:24:49,840 --> 00:24:53,520
I care a lot about adoption metrics in our applicant tracking system, our recruiting product,

309
00:24:53,520 --> 00:24:56,640
because it's in a really good place from a usability standpoint.

310
00:24:56,640 --> 00:24:58,080
It's very well instrumented.

311
00:24:58,080 --> 00:25:00,159
It's got like very happy users.

312
00:25:00,159 --> 00:25:02,640
Um it's got an awesome growth profile.

313
00:25:02,640 --> 00:25:09,279
And so we should we should be really focused on the adoption metrics because I think that's going to be an important ingredient to low churn over time.

314
00:25:09,279 --> 00:25:13,120
You know, removing friction from the implementation process as an example.

315
00:25:13,120 --> 00:25:24,159
There are other parts of our product where I would say I don't care at all about adoption and am much more focused on foundational things like I said earlier test coverage or whatever just to make sure that the thing is stable

316
00:25:24,159 --> 00:25:28,240
and good and delivering exactly what it's supposed to deliver to deliver once it's adopted.

317
00:25:28,240 --> 00:25:34,000
Now that you're on the inside of the product team, what's something that you think people outside of product,

318
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:44,480
say Matt two years ago or other, I don't know, go to market leads, other execs, uh, should hear need to understand about product that they don't until they're on the inside.

319
00:25:44,480 --> 00:25:48,000
I'll give you another framework that I like to use.

320
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:52,000
In the financial world, there's this concept of alpha.

321
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:56,159
Alpha is outperformance relative to the index.

322
00:25:56,159 --> 00:26:00,240
So that's why you have seekingalfalpha.com as a very popular website.

323
00:26:00,240 --> 00:26:06,720
What they mean by that is you're looking to buy something, some combination of assets that will outperform,

324
00:26:06,720 --> 00:26:09,360
let's say, the S&P 500 if that's your benchmark.

325
00:26:09,360 --> 00:26:12,480
So alpha is the outperformance relative to the index.

326
00:26:12,480 --> 00:26:14,000
And then you have the concept of beta.

327
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:15,360
Beta is just volatility.

328
00:26:15,360 --> 00:26:16,480
Beta is not good.

329
00:26:16,480 --> 00:26:20,480
A high beta stock jerks around for no particular reason.

330
00:26:20,480 --> 00:26:22,720
It's like disorrelated with the index.

331
00:26:22,720 --> 00:26:24,320
It just, you know, it's very high beta.

332
00:26:24,320 --> 00:26:28,000
great if you're an options trader, but other than that, it's not really something you want in an asset.

333
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:33,760
And so, your ideal stock is a very high alpha, very low beta stock.

334
00:26:33,760 --> 00:26:40,720
They don't really come in that shape because alpha and beta tend to be correlated, but that's what you want when you buy a financial asset.

335
00:26:40,720 --> 00:26:42,799
So, what's the analogy?

336
00:26:42,799 --> 00:26:47,840
I think you have high alpha people who are very valuable.

337
00:26:47,840 --> 00:26:53,279
I think you also have low beta people who are also very valuable people.

338
00:26:53,279 --> 00:27:00,559
Um, Dennis Rodman, basketball player, nut job, very high alpha.

339
00:27:00,559 --> 00:27:03,200
And you know, there's room on every team for one.

340
00:27:03,200 --> 00:27:05,279
Dennis Rodman is a favorite of mine.

341
00:27:05,279 --> 00:27:10,880
It's like you can have one difficult employee who's got a ton of upside.

342
00:27:10,880 --> 00:27:22,320
Um, and so this alpha beta thing, I use it pretty often when contemplating what kind of person I want and also what kind of process I want.

343
00:27:22,320 --> 00:27:27,679
So when you're building a product from 0 to one, you're probably pursu pursuing alpha.

344
00:27:27,679 --> 00:27:36,799
You're looking for some angle on this market or this customer problem where the product is actually going to provide an outsiz return relative to whatever the default solution is.

345
00:27:36,799 --> 00:27:40,240
When you have a more mature product or if you have somebody in the product operations group or whatever,

346
00:27:40,240 --> 00:27:43,200
you probably want a more low beta environment where it's like it cranks it out.

347
00:27:43,200 --> 00:27:44,159
It does it very reliably.

348
00:27:44,159 --> 00:27:48,320
Our payroll product, we badly want the payroll product to be very low beta.

349
00:27:48,320 --> 00:27:52,000
We really don't want the payroll product to have any unpredictability or aberration.

350
00:27:52,000 --> 00:27:55,039
And so we're [clears throat] willing to accept more process.

351
00:27:55,039 --> 00:28:05,520
And here's a fundamental principle of design in an organization which is that processes processes in a business exist for the

352
00:28:05,520 --> 00:28:08,960
sole purpose of lowering beta.

353
00:28:08,960 --> 00:28:15,600
Processes are for decreasing volatility in the output of the system.

354
00:28:15,600 --> 00:28:19,840
The the the downside of a process is that it suppresses alpha.

355
00:28:19,840 --> 00:28:30,399
And you have to be super super careful and judicious in the application of process in the product team to know that you're lowering beta in the

356
00:28:30,399 --> 00:28:34,799
places where you want to do that without suppressing alpha in the places where you need it.

357
00:28:34,799 --> 00:28:41,520
And so as we've gone through the last, you know, year of reforming the way that we build product at Ripwing,

358
00:28:41,520 --> 00:28:47,039
it's been a game of recognizing those places where I need to implement a touch of process,

359
00:28:47,039 --> 00:28:48,559
just a touch.

360
00:28:48,559 --> 00:28:54,159
Other places where I need to implement a very clear rigid process where I don't want alpha,

361
00:28:54,159 --> 00:28:55,679
I just want low beta.

362
00:28:55,679 --> 00:29:00,559
And so examples of this are, let's say, our product quality list, which we lovingly at Riplin call the pickle.

363
00:29:00,559 --> 00:29:01,360
>> Why pickle?

364
00:29:01,360 --> 00:29:01,600
Yeah.

365
00:29:01,600 --> 00:29:02,960
So it's actually a really important thing.

366
00:29:02,960 --> 00:29:08,480
I think if you want to bring about cultural change in a team, like look, we have we have 1300 people in our R&D organization.

367
00:29:08,480 --> 00:29:10,399
It's a big ship that we have to steer.

368
00:29:10,399 --> 00:29:16,080
If you want to create a moment that sticks in people's brains and sort of becomes a zeitgeist or something that they latch on to,

369
00:29:16,080 --> 00:29:22,799
you got to create an entity, a vessel for meaning, and then you got to fill that vessel with your meaning.

370
00:29:22,799 --> 00:29:24,000
A meme, you might say.

371
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:24,240
>> Yeah.

372
00:29:24,240 --> 00:29:24,799
Well, sure.

373
00:29:24,799 --> 00:29:31,120
a meme like a meme is actually a good example of this in common culture, you know, and um I in pop culture,

374
00:29:31,120 --> 00:29:36,559
I think like it's why when when people come to the table with with with ideas from the outside,

375
00:29:36,559 --> 00:29:43,440
I welcome those outside ideas, but if the first thing I ask the person to do is to tell me what they mean without using those words.

376
00:29:43,440 --> 00:29:46,080
So when someone comes in and says, "Hey, I want to do this thing on strategy."

377
00:29:46,080 --> 00:29:50,320
I'm like, "Cool, tell me what you mean without using the word strategy."

378
00:29:50,320 --> 00:29:52,960
And it forces them to break it down into its constituent parts.

379
00:29:52,960 --> 00:29:56,720
And if they can articulate it clearly without using that word, I know that they know what they're talking about.

380
00:29:56,720 --> 00:30:01,039
And if they just fumble around with the word strategy again, I'm like, okay, you actually haven't thought this through.

381
00:30:01,039 --> 00:30:06,480
And so with the pickle, with the product quality list, it's like I could come up with some generic term for this,

382
00:30:06,480 --> 00:30:11,440
but I really want a new joiner at the company to understand that this is an idiosyncratic thing to rippling.

383
00:30:11,440 --> 00:30:12,720
This is unique to us.

384
00:30:12,720 --> 00:30:14,399
You you want to understand this thing.

385
00:30:14,399 --> 00:30:21,360
I also want it to become a component of common parliament in the day-to-day work of the product management and engineering teams.

386
00:30:21,360 --> 00:30:30,640
And so pickle, as cheeky or silly as it sounds, was deliberately sort of angular or stood out as a vessel I could fill with a particular meaning.

387
00:30:30,640 --> 00:30:32,080
And so we have a product quality list.

388
00:30:32,080 --> 00:30:41,760
And the product quality list is lightweight in the sense that it just articulates in the simplest ways the standards we want you to meet when you ship a product.

389
00:30:41,760 --> 00:30:42,880
Doesn't apply to every product.

390
00:30:42,880 --> 00:30:50,480
Not every line applies to every product, but it's comprehensive and it provides me with a framework for iterating over time as we learn.

391
00:30:50,480 --> 00:30:54,159
And so just yesterday, we shipped the product to Parker.

